title: For Sale:  USED - 1937 CZ 24, .380ACP, 1 Mag
postcontent: USED - This is a late 1937 production CZ Model 1924 (vz. 24), in .380 ACP, with one mag that was the standard Czechoslovak Army pistol of the inter-war period. It was manufactured by Česka Zbrojovka (CZ) in Prague (as displayed on a rib on the top of the slide “Česka Zbrojovka A.S. v Praze”). It has 97-98% of its original bright blue finish remaining with only minor holster wear at the muzzle. The trigger, hammer, and extractor retain about 90% of the original straw color. While similar looking, this is not a CZ 27 pistol. CZ 24 was an improved version of the CZ 22, which had been licensed from Mauser. Production of the CZ 24 started in August 1925. The original order for 20,000 pistols was completed in June 1926. Overall, approximately 200,000 CZ 24 pistols were made. An inventory on January 1, 1939, showed the Czechoslovak Army and Air Force had on hand 171,756 CZ 24 pistols. The regular serial number range for the CZ 24 pistol is: 12,000-190,000. The serial number of this pistol is 173,774. The pistol displays the 1937 acceptance “J, rampant lion, 37” mark of Czechoslovak Military. CZ 24 is a meticulously crafted, well-built, robust, and reliable pistol that was very highly thought of at the time. During the German occupation (March 1939 – May 1945), the Czechoslovak Armed Forces were disarmed, and all the weapons were utilized by Germany and its allies. The CZ 24 pistols were not marked by the Germans, in any way, except for those used by the German Navy. CZ 24 pistols were also issued to the German Air Force, and Waffen-SS. Magazine capacity is eight rounds, and a Mauser Model 1910-style safety switch is mounted to the left of the pistol. This pistol has the original high polish blue finish, strawed small parts (straw color is generous). Unlike early CZ 24 pistols fitted with one-piece wood grips, our later (production) CZ 24 is fitted with original one-piece checkered Bakelite (early plastic) excellent grips with no cracks or chips, with the “ČZ” logos molded on the top. The pistol is housed in an original Czech-manufactured leather flap holster. While CZ 24 pistols are quite common, it is difficult to find one in such exceptional condition. It would make a fine addition to any collection.

title: For Sale:  USED - CZ 27 Semi-Auto Pistol, 7.65MM(32ACP), 1 mag, Extra Barrel
postcontent: USED - CZECH CZ 27 EXTREMELY RARE PRE-WAR “CESKA” VARIATION PISTOL IN 7.65MM (32ACP).  Icludes one mag, holster and extra barrel (see description).This is a VERY HARD-TO-FIND early, “Ceska” variation, CZ 27 with a serial number of 18,740. The CZ 27 pistol is broken down into three variations: “Ceska”, “Bohmische”, and the “fnh” variation. “Ceska” variation of pre-war CZ 27 pistols, with slide top inscription in the Czech language “ČESKA ZBROJOVKA A. S. v PRAZE”, is extremely rare. This inscription was only used on pre-World War II, early Occupation (1940), and post-War (1945/46) vz. 27 pistols. Beginning in early 1940, this slide top inscription bears the German wording “BÖHMISCHE WAFFENFABRIK A.G. IN PRAG” etc. The “Ceska” inscription is found on early CZ 27 pistols with serial numbers ranging from 16,000 to 21,400. Thus, only 5,400 of these pre-war pistols were manufactured! CZ pistol collectors, most likely you will never see this rare CZ 27 variation again. Note the four ANGLED slide grasping grooves on this rare CZ 27 pistol rather than the vertical grooves on CZ 27 pistols of (Nazi) German manufacture and post-World War II Czechoslovak manufacture! This is very rare. This CZ 27 pistol is one of three groupings of pistols that exhibit the letters “DR” in a circle on the left side upper web of the trigger guard. These three apparent groups fall between the serial number range of 16,000 to 34,000 and were manufactured between early 1940 and late 1941. They followed the GECO and AKAH (large German sporting goods dealers) contracts. Our CZ 27 is also a contract pistol and the letters “DR” stand for “Deutsche Reichsbahn”, the German railway system (German railway property marking). When the slide top markings were changed from “Ceska” to “Bohmische”, the German designation for the CZ 27 and the caliber were added to the left side of the slide (our pistol doesn’t have them). Magazine bottoms were marked P.MOD.27. NOTE: Our pistol has one flaw, without which it would have been priced at over $3,000. The previous owner of this pistol tampered with the original matching barrel (serial number 18,740) in an attempt to repair or modify it. This is nothing that a good gun smith cannot fix. The pistol is equipped with a Nazi-era replacement barrel (serial number 197,972) stamped with an “eagle clutching a swastika” German Military test proof mark. The original barrel that comes with the pistol is also stamped with the same proof mark. All the numbered parts are matching. In March 1939, Nazi Germany occupied all of Czechoslovakia, and in early 1941, all CZ 27 pistol production was diverted to the German war effort. Czechoslovak sources put the beginning serial number of German Military production at 20,500 (the serial number of our early pistol is 18,740). Between 620,000 and 650,000 CZ 27 pistols were manufactured in total, 452,500 of those.-

title: For Sale:  USED - CZ 38 Pistol, .380ACP, DAO, 1 Mag, Holster
postcontent: CZECH CZ 38 PISTOL WITH HOLSTERThis item a seldom seen Czech made double action only, .380 ACP CZ 38 pistol in good condition with some dings and wear on the finish. A nice crisp holster is also included. The CZ 38, also known as vz. 38 and P39(t), is a Semi-automatic pistol designed by František Myška and manufactured from 1939 until 1945. The barrel is attached to the frame by a hinge, allowing for very easy disassembly. CZ 38 is a very well built pistol with many great innovations. The frame slide and barrel have the Czechoslovak Military proof. Pushing the grooved latch below the factory marking forward allows the barrel and slide to pivot upward for disassembly. The pivot pin, unusually, is below the muzzle. This Czechoslovak Army contract CZ 38 pistol has the circled CZ, trademark of the Česká Zbrojovka factory, and Czechoslovak Military acceptance mark (E7 lion 39). E is the mark of the Ordnance Technical office, 7 is the location number of office (7 was at Česká Zbrojovka Factory in Strakonice), 39 was the year of acceptance. On June 14, 1938, the Ministry of Defense ordered from the Česká Zbrojovka 41,000 vz. 38 pistols with serial numbers ranging from 250,000 to 291,000 (our pistol’s serial number is 287,674). In March, 1939 Germany occupied all of Czechoslovakia. Nazis allowed for the military contract to be completed, but the pistols would be issued to German units already armed with Czechoslovak weapons (most of the pistols saw service in Greater German police and security forces). The Czechoslovak Military never did receive any of their new vz. 38 pistols. Approximately 45,000 CZ 38 pistols were manufactured in total. The vz. 38 was designated by the Germans as P39(t), Pistole 39 Tschechoslowakei (the German spelling for Czechoslovakia). A German secret Military equipment list dated January 7, 1943, identifies the CZ 38 pistol as Military Equipment Number 2002. The serial number range is from 250,000 to 290,999 (our pistol’s serial number is 287,674). A hard-shell holster was issued to most of the P39(t) pistols. Some pistols (including ours), were issued a soft type German-made holster.

title: For Sale:  USED - CZ 38 Pistol, .380ACP, DAO, 1 Mag, Nazi Holster
postcontent: CZECH CZ 38 EXCELLENT CONDITION PISTOL WITH RARE HARD-SHELL NAZI HOLSTER. This item is a seldom seen Czech made double action only CZ 38 pistol chambered in .380 ACP. One magazine and an original Nazi hard-shell holster is included. CZ 38 pistol in excellent condition with excellent finish overall. This pistol includes a nice crisp 1940 dated holster. The CZ 38, also known as vz. 38 and P39(t), is a Semi-automatic pistol designed by František Myška and manufactured from 1939 until 1945. The barrel is attached to the frame by a hinge, allowing for very easy disassembly. CZ 38 is a very well built pistol with many great innovations. The frame slide and barrel have the Czechoslovak Military proof. Pushing the grooved latch below the factory marking forward allows the barrel and slide to pivot upward for disassembly. The pivot pin, unusually, is below the muzzle. This Czechoslovak Army contract CZ 38 pistol has the circled CZ, trademark of the Česká Zbrojovka factory, and Czechoslovak Military acceptance mark (E7 lion 39). E is the mark of the Ordnance Technical office, 7 is the location number of office (7 was at Česká Zbrojovka Factory in Strakonice), 39 was the year of acceptance (our pistol was accepted in September, 1939). On June 14, 1938, the Ministry of Defense ordered from the Česká Zbrojovka 41,000 vz 38 pistols with serial numbers ranging from 250,000 to 291,000 (our pistol’s serial number is 252,030). In March, 1939 Germany occupied all of Czechoslovakia. Nazis allowed for the military contract to be completed, but the pistols would be issued to German units already armed with Czechoslovak weapons (most of the pistols saw service in Greater German police and security forces). The Czechoslovak Military never did receive any of their new vz 38 pistols. Approximately 45,000 CZ 38 pistols were manufactured in total. The vz 38 was designated by the Germans as P39(t), Pistole 39 Tschechoslowakei (the German spelling for Czechoslovakia). A German secret Military equipment list dated January 7, 1943, identifies the CZ 38 pistol as Military Equipment Number 2002. The serial number range is from 250,000 to 290,999 (our pistol’s serial number is 252,030). A hard-shell holster was issued and so marked for this pistol. Today collectors often mistake the holster for a P.38 holster as they are almost indistinguishable. Nearly all German-made holsters for the P39(t) are dated 1940. Our pistol comes with the original German-made black leather holster displaying marks “P39(t)” and “Aug. 1940”. It also comes with two magazines.

title: For Sale:  Tennessee Valley Tulle (Fusil de Chasse)
postcontent: Lightly used, steel furniture, custom made Tennessee Valley Muzzleloading Tulle .62 caliber smooth bore. Well cared for and cleaned after each use. Only shot blanks through it for re-enactment purposes.From website:Tulle (Fusil de Chasse)The TVM Tulle is not an exact replica of any specific Tulle. The lines and style portray a Tulle hunting gun instead of a military version. There were thousands of Tulles fusils shipped to New France in the late 17th and early 18th centuries. According to "Frontier Guns" by T.M. Hamilton, there were two types of them built. The first was a type C (1680 to 1730) and the second was a type D (1730 to 1765). They are alike in the shape of the stock with variations in the furniture. Ours shares the same basic stock shape with the trigger guard and buttplate of Type D. It comes with an A grade stock, right handed L&R flintlock, 20 gauge smoothbore (.62 caliber), 42" barrel length, brass or steel furniture, single trigger, deluxe, round thimbles, serpent sideplate, and your length of pull. This can also be built left-handed, but will require using a different lock.Willing to ship $50 flat rate in US$1000.00, cash or PayPal only. Thanks for looking!
